/*************************************************** JAVA *************************************************/

 Optimal Solution - We iteratively compare nodes from both sorted lists, attach the smaller one to the result list, 
                      and finally append any remaining nodes to produce a merged sorted list.


class Solution {
    public ListNode mergeTwoLists(ListNode list1, ListNode list2) {
        // Dummy node to simplify edge cases
        ListNode returnNode = new ListNode(Integer.MIN_VALUE);
        // Pointer to build the merged list
        ListNode headNode = returnNode;
        // Traverse both lists while both have nodes
        while (list1 != null && list2 != null) {
            // Attach the smaller node to the merged list
            if (list1.val <= list2.val) {
                returnNode.next = list1;
                list1 = list1.next;
            } else {
                returnNode.next = list2;
                list2 = list2.next;
            }
            // Move the pointer forward
            returnNode = returnNode.next;
        }
        // Attach the remaining nodes (only one list can be non-empty)
        if (list1 == null) {
            returnNode.next = list2;
        } else {
            returnNode.next = list1;
        }
        // Return the merged list (skipping dummy node)
        return headNode.next;
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(m + n) ~ list1 , list2
Space Comlexity :- O(1).
